@Node About "Abstrax/About"
                              About This Demo
                              ---------------

The AbstraxPig demo was produced over an (intermittent) period of two
months, by Vivid Software, mainly to show that the AGA chipset is capable
of a lot more than just showing a graduated copperlist, or 4 bitplane
dual-playfield.

The demo is totally configurable at assemble-time, and we had to leave out
some of our more common routines (a real 3D dot-tunnel for example) because
we have only just fitted into the memory of an A1200 by around 3 kilobytes.
(Which gave us one HELL of a panic when we had to decrunch a 1.4 megabyte
executable on a 2 megabyte A1200 with the system fully alive! Thanks,
Imploder!). All memory is allocated in real-time, as you will see if you
have a serial terminal!

There are a couple of @{"preferences" Link Prefs} available to you from AmigaDOS, and a few
hidden (WELL hidden) ones to boot.

The demo fully supports being run from WorkBench, if you have enough bytes.
This demo requires just under 1,814,000 bytes to run, and scrapes through on
a dual-drive A1200 with no harddisk by about 4k. If you have 2 drives and a
harddisk, but only 2 megabytes, you will certainly need to turn one diskdrive
off. To run the demo from WorkBench, you will need around 1.5 megs of free
chip-ram, and 512k of public memory. The public memory can be in fairly small
fragments, as AbstraxPig is made of 81 fully relocatable hunks, that can be
scatter-loaded all through public memory. We want to thank the Authors of
Turbo Imploder v4 for their marvellous cruncher, that can decrunch an
executable file of such a massive size into such a small amount of memory
** WITHOUT FRAGMENTING A BYTE! ** Without this program, our demo would need
to be on a High Density disk, unable to be read by you 1200 owners! Please
feel free to decrunch the demo onto an HD floppy or your HardDrive. The demo
is perfectly safe of your harddisk, but don't come moaning to us if it
formats it or something...


This demo has been a simultaneous production with our AGA game...

           * MR GURK AND HIS AmAzInG 16 MILLION COLOURED QUEST *

which will be released in the (fairly) near future. The demo utilises the
same system (VSLib) that we are using to produce the game. The system
allows us to use the full potential of the AGA chipset, without having to
mess around with the contrived (but downwards compatible) architecture.
@EndNode

@Node Funstick "Abstrax/Funstick"

There are a few little controls you might like to know in this demo. On the
part with the scrolling (and maybe colour cycling - depending on your
preference env settings) Mandelbrot set, you can press these things:

Funstick -	Grab it and move it up & down, left & right to scroll around
		the set. Hold fire and push forward to zoom into the set,
		towards the point at the centre of the screen (but you'll never
		reach it, by the way) or hold fire and pull back to zoom out.

Mouse -		Press right mouse button to get a new random place on the set.

Keyboard -	Press the keys CTRL + LAMIGA + RAMIGA to go for a REAL trip
		to Mars!

@EndNode
@Node Prefs

There are three preferences that you may set for customizing the AbstraxPig.
They are all AmigaDOS Environmental variables, stored in ENV:AbstraxPig

    Reset(Yes/No)	--	Defines whether or not the demo
				re-boots at the end, or just continues with
				whatever it was doing. This ENV is mainly
				here for our computer shop owning friends
				who want an AGA demo that loops to run in-store.

    CyclePan(Yes/No)	--	Defines whether the scrolling
				Mandelbrot set is to colour cycle or not.

    Endcycle(Yes/No)	--	Defines whether to colour cycle the
				beautiful 8 bitplane mandelbrot at the end.

For example, if you wanted the demo to reboot at the end instead of just
going on forever, you would type at the Shell:-

1> SetEnv AbstraxPig/Reset Yes

or

1> SetEnv CyclePan No

If you wanted your brain-cells to remain intact for a bit longer...

If you have an A4000/030 uncomment the CPU line in the Startup-Sequence
@EndNode

